The federal government has come under attack over the parlous state of the economy, as expert express concerns that the dwindling external reserves is a cause of worry. Citing data obtained from the Central bank of Nigeria (CBN) website which shows that the reserves stood at $39.42 billion last Wednesday, May 4th 2022 compared to the $39.81 billion it stood on April 21, Maxwell Nsofor, an economic analyst, said this indicates that the reserves dropped in two weeks by $384 million.   Winners emerge in Union Bank, Mobo game competition     Fed Govt approves N3bn Sukuk fund for Numan-Jalingo road     First Lady tasks Lagosians on mental healthcare   This is coming as the federal government announced that the balance in the Excess Crude Account, as of April 27, 2022, stood at a paltry $35.372 million. The ECA is a savings account retained by the federal government and is funded by the difference between the market price of crude oil and the budgeted price of crude oil as contained in the appropriation bill.